    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Goblins? Oh, you're asking about the *goblins* again? My apologies, I seem to have gotten momentarily distracted by the sheer *potential* for mischief in the regulatory landscape. It's like seeing a perfectly stacked pile of shiny trinkets and suddenly forgetting the spreadsheet.\n\nTo answer your core question, if a building's footprint *slightly* encroaches on the required setback line, you are in the realm of \"variance\" or \"exception.\" This is where the real bureaucratic goblins live, and they are notoriously difficult to appease. You can't just sneak a little bit of your building out, as a small, sneaky goblin might try to sneak a mushroom past the watchman.\n\nTo get that encroachment approved, you typically need to apply for a variance from the local planning department. You'll have to demonstrate that the encroachment doesn't cause undue hardship or negatively impact the public good—meaning, you have to convince the city that your tiny bit of trespass won't cause a whole goblin raid on the neighbors. You'll need detailed site plans, and frankly, you'll need a very persuasive argument, perhaps involving a very shiny, non-threatening offering.\n\nAs for the setbacks",
      "source": "target",
